Fix SETTLE in TPR parser  (#2068) * Fix SETTLE in TPR parser

Support for SETTLE interactions in the TPR parser was added in #1953.
Though, the support was only added for the older versions of the TPR
format, causing errors with the newest files. In practice, when reading
the bonds on a recent TPR file containing SETTLE constraints, the
indices to the atoms involved in the bonds would be shifted. This is
because, the older TPR files use a different format to describe SETTLE
constraints.

This commit should fix the issue by supporting both the old and the new
format for SETTLE.

* Adapt the test to make sure the SETTLE issue is caught

The test for SETTLE in TPR now checks that the index are not shifted.

Should the first data point be always 1? In that case first tau = 0. Or should the first data point reflect the first tau which is non-zero and therefore the first change is quantified? Changed expected output from 0.0 to Nan. The survival probability is a measure of how likely a selected molecule
is to remain within a specified region over a period of time. If at t0
the selected molecule is not in the specified region, no survival
probability can be calculated.

For example, consider that we would like to calculate the survival
probability of an ion at an interface. If the ion never approaches the
interface, the previous test would return a survival probability of 0,
which suggests that the ion comes to the interface but leaves
immediately. However, as the ion was never at the interface, no
survival probability can be calculated from this data.

Add a faster function to deduplicate indices `mda.lib.cutil.unique_int_1d` takes a 1D array of integers and returns
an array of the unique values. It has similar perormances as
`np.unique` for randomly ordered values, but is faster for sorted values.

MDAnalysis needs to deduplicate arrays of indices for basic operations.
In most cases the indices are sorted so the deduplication can be done
in linear complexity. However, `np.unique` is a general function; it
systematically sorts the values with a quicksort, which makes the
complexity in the order of n log n.

`mda.lib.cutil.unique_int_1d` only works on 1D arrays of integer and
does not have the optional return values `np.unique` has. It assumes
first that the values are sorted and only sorts them if they happen not
to be.

Fixed MPI fork() warning when importing MDAnalysis after MPI_Init() call Solved problem:
---------------
When used in an MPI environment, importing MDAnalysis may trigger an MPI
warning because importing the uuid module in MDAnalysis.core.universe
triggers a call to os.fork(). This happens if MPI_Init() has been called
prior to importing MDAnalysis.

Why this was fixed:
-------------------
For the user, it is completely unclear where and why the MPI warning was
triggered and whether that is of any concern.

How to reproduce:
-----------------
With OpenMPI (version should be irrelevant, tested on 1.10.2) and Python < 3.7, executing
the command
  echo "import mpi4py.MPI, MDAnalysis" | mpirun --mca mpi_warn_on_fork 1 -n 1 python -
yields the following output:

"""
An MPI process has executed an operation involving a call to the
"fork()" system call to create a child process.  Open MPI is currently
operating in a condition that could result in memory corruption or
other system errors; your MPI job may hang, crash, or produce silent
data corruption.  The use of fork() (or system() or other calls that
create child processes) is strongly discouraged.  

The process that invoked fork was:

  Local host:          <hostname> (PID <pid>)
  MPI_COMM_WORLD rank: 0

If you are *absolutely sure* that your application will successfully
and correctly survive a call to fork(), you may disable this warning
by setting the mpi_warn_on_fork MCA parameter to 0.
"""

If you cannot reproduce this warning, it is probably due to your Python
installation using an implementation of fork() that is named differently and,
thus, is not recognized by mpirun (can be checked for example with gdb).

Explanation:
------------
The problem is actually caused by the uuid module, which is imported in
MDAnalysis.core.universe and triggers a call to os.fork() by calling a couple
of methods from the ctypes module which in turn use the subprocess module
(that's where os.fork() actually gets called).
This means that the real problem is not due to MDAnalysis itself, but it also
means that it will probably never be fixed for older Python versions.
In Python 3.7, the problem with the uuid module is solved. (see
https://bugs.python.org/issue11063 for further information)
Luckily, for Python < 3.7, the uuid module works perfectly fine with
os.fork() disabled during its import.
A clean fix is therefore simply to disable os.fork() prior to importing the
uuid module in MDAnalysis.core.universe and to re-enable it afterwards (for
Python < 3.7 only).

fix header length information in dcd A DCD has two byte positions to store the length of the remark section. First a
it reads number of bytes in the remark plus 4. Afterwards it has the number of
80 character sections. These two numbers have to match. So far we wrote first
that we use 164 chars and three 80 character blocks, 164 != 80*3 + 4

Now we corrected that and state correctly we write 244 bytes in the remark
section. We never noticed that because our reader ignores the information about
the byte length on looks only at the number of blocks.

As a side note here. DCD remarks always have have to be a multiple of 80 in
length.

Add a molnums topology attribute to TPR parser PR #1557 introduced the moltype attribute that gives a name to each kind
of molecule in a topology. This commit adds the related molnums
attribute that gives an index to each individual molecules.

The molnums attributes allows to split a system by molecule without
ambiguity when the attribute is defines. Without this commit, the only
way of splitting a system per molecule is `atom_group.fragments`. While
it works most of the time, it can fail in some topology that use other
topology tricks than bonds to connect atoms; this is the case in gromacs
with virtual sites for instance. Fragments can also be time consuming on
large systems. This commits allows to slit a system per molecule without
ambiguity with `atom_group.groupby('molnums')` or
`atom_group.split('molecule')`.

This commit also adds the `molnum` selection keyword. To do so, this
commit refactored `mda.core.selection.SelectionRange` to avoid code
duplication.

Issue 1555 moltype (#1557) * Add moltypes as topology attribute for TPR

The TPR parser now exposes the molecule type as the moltypes topology
attribute. The moltypes attribute is defined at the residue level, but
can be accessed at the atom level as well; it behave in the same way as
the resnames attribute.

The molecule type is the name of the molecule to which the atom/residue
belongs. Two molecules that share a molecule type has the same topology
template, so by definition they will have the same number of atoms,
residue, bonds, angles ... On the contrary to segments, moltypes do not
have to be contiguous so multiple occurrences of the same moltype can be
defined in a topology with other molecule types in between; this happens
for instance in lipid bilayer simulations where the lipids are sorted by
leaflet.

In the specific case of gromacs, the molecule type is defined as the
first field in the `[moleculetype]` section of an ITP file. Only the TPR
parser implements the moltype attribute, though the attribute is generic
in principle and can be implemented in any other parser assuming the
format can name molecules.

Fix deprecation warning missfires (#1477) * Fix deprecation warning missfires

`u.segments` and `u.residues` should not issue a deprecation warning.
This commit applies the same strategy than
a9f9655a3b45b8486a1aadb5ad903f8bfe68ef3f to avoid the unwanted warning.

* Ignore `exec-used` pylint warning in a test

The exec built-in is used in the tests about the deprecation warnings
for the instant selectors. This causes a warning from pylint as `exec`
can be a security concern in some context. Here, the input given to
`exec` is fully controlled and exec is not more dangerous than typing
the input instructions directly. As `exec` improves the readability of
the tests, this commit disable the warning for the two specific use of
`exec`.

Merge pull request #1393 from MDAnalysis/issue-1362-int_types Issue #1362 : use np.intp types for indexing instead of np.int64

- According to numpy/numpy#4384 (comment), `np.intp` is the recommended dtype for indexing:
   "... use np.intp as dtype whenever things have to do with indexing or are logically related to 
   indexing/array sizes. This is the natural dtype for it and it will normally also be the fastest one.
- see https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/user/basics.types.html
- see also PR #1391 for discussion
- This change should go some way towards increasing compatibility with i386/i696 (32 bit) platforms.

Avoid isinstance(something, int) Testing that arguments where integer by using `isinstance(arg, int)` has
proven itself detrimental on several occasions. Indeed, the test refuses
other types that would be legitimate such as numpy integers. This commit
replaces the remaining occurences of the too narrow test by the solution
that has already been used on multiple places of the code: testing
against `numbers.Integral`. This new way matches everything that looks
enough like an integer, and behave the same on python 2 and python 3 on
the contrary to testing against `int`.

Fix the number of frames in transfer_to_memory pm The number of frames passed to the progress meter by transfer_to_memory
was wrong, especially in the case of truncated trajectory.

This commit pass the correct number of frames to the progress meter, and
adapt the progression message.

Fix transfer_to_memory progress meter call Since I merged #1030, Universe.transfer_to_memory could instanciate a
ProgressMeter with an invalid interval. By default, that interval was
set to None, which is an invalid interval since interval must be an
integer (or must be castable to an int).

Here, I make sure Universe.transfer_to_memory always use 1 as interval
for the progress meter. This leads to the same behaviour as before #1030
was merged: the progress meter updates at every frame transferred. Note
that this behavior is not the default behavior of the progress meter,
and that the default behavior may be preferable.

lib.util.Namespace raises the expected exception (#1169) * lib.util.Namespace raises the expected exception

`lib.util.Namespace` allows to query a namespace by index or by
attribute. It allows to use both the following syntaxes to access the
same element:

    ns = lib.util.Namespace()
    ns['key'] = 'plop'

    ns['key']  # Access by index
    ns.key  # Access by attribute

The class is used to permit some flexibility when accessing auxiliary
data attached to trajectories.

Prior to this commit, accessing a non-existing item from a namespace by
attribute would raise a KeyError while an AttributeError should be
raise. This breaks functions that test the features of an object by
looking for some attributes, and are therefore capturing AttributeError
as a sign the attribute is missing.

In particular, raising the wrong exception confused
`numpy.lib.type_check.iscomplexobj` in numpy 1.12.0. This confusion lead
to `assert_equal` to miss behave in that version of numpy, therefore
breaking the tests for MDAnalysis when upgrading from python 1.11.3 to
1.12.0.

This commit makes sure that the expected exception is raised when
accessing an non-existing item by attribute in a Namespace object.

Deprecate quiet in hbond_analysis MDAnalysis.analysis.hbonds.hbond_analysis is a peculiar case for the
deprecation of the *quiet* keyword argument in favor of *verbose*.
Indeed, the *verbose* keyword argument is already in use to toggle the
debug outputs.

Here we deprecate the use of *quiet* in favor of *verbose*, and we
deprecate the use of *verbose* in favor of *debug*. A deprecation
warning is issued in two cases:

* the user creates an instance of HydrogenBondAnalysis using the
  *verbose* keyword argument. In this case, the user wants to set up the
  debug mode and should have used *debug* in the new version.
* the user calls HydrogenBondAnalysis.run with the *quiet* argument.
  There, the user wants to toggle the progress meter and should use
  *verbose*.

If the user calls HydrogenBondAnalysis.run with the *verbose* keyword
argument, then we cannot now if he intended to toggle the progress meter
following the new usage, or to set the debug output following the old
usage. Therefore, such call cannot issue a deprecation warning. Yet, the
change in behavior is visible as soon as the first step of the analysis.

a deprecation warning as it is not a documented API; it could issue a

Instructions on how to deal with the post deprecation phase are added in
the docstring of the new private function lib.log._set_verbose. Thet
function handles most of the logic behing the deprecation of the quiet
keyword. It issues the deprecation warning if needed, raises an
exception if the user provided contradictory values of quiet and
verbose, and gives the value of verbose based on verbose and quiet.

gmx_fio_do_string, and read the size prior to the string.

ProgressMeter accepts both new and legacy formats A previous commit, translated the formats from the legacy to the new
syntax. This would break user's code.

This commit adds a keyword `format_handling`. When the keyword is set to
"new", the format string is handled with the new {}-based syntax. When
the keyword is set to "legacy", the format string is handled with the
old %-based syntax. By default, the keyword is set to "auto"; then the
kind of syntax is guessed.
streamlined convergence functions
Document changes to ProgressMeter in CHAMGELOG Also add a .. versionchanged:: entry.

Progress meter format do not contain \r anymore The implementation details of the progress meter should not be the
responsibility of the end user. Therefore, the end user should not have
to deal with the \r at the beginning of its custom format for the
progress meter. This is especially True as having the \r at the
beginning or at the end of the format may cause different behavior.

This commit removes the responsibility of the \r from the end user.
Instead, it adds a `dynamic` keyword to the ProgressMeter class. If set
to True (default), the \r is added at the beginning. Else, the format is
left untouched.

Fix progress bar in jupyter notebook Fixes #927

Place the \r at the beginning of the format rather than at the end. This
caused the progress bar not to be displayed on jupyter notebooks.

This commit also change the string formatting of the progress bar from
the old % syntax to the new {} one.

The old HOLE test trajectory XTC_HOLE was replaced with MULTIPDB_HOLE.
The old one contained repetitions of a static frame, the new one the dominant
mode from an elastic network model (generated by elNemo server). The new one
is a better example for future test cases and also to demonstrate the
function of the module --- see eg https://gist.github.com/orbeckst/64c0bd5a037b3e434cc8ee6732030252

  generator; this allows reproducible HOLE runs

  (and which *rely* on having RASEED --- otherwise each run
  gives different output)

   tar xvf  hole2-NotForProfit-2.2.004-Linux-x86_64.tar.gz
   export PATH=${PATH}:${HOME}/hole2/exe

There is also a Mac OS X version:

   curl -L 'https://www.dropbox.com/s/5mzrsyp48i32je4/hole2-NotForProfit-2.2.004-Darwin-i386.tar.gz?dl=1' -o hole2-NotForProfit-2.2.004-Darwin-i386.tar.gz

All deprecations on AtomGroup and friends getters and setters. (#698) * All deprecations on AtomGroup and friends getters and setters.

The new topology system for #363 will arrive in 0.16.0, and this removes
redundant getters and setters of various `Atom`, `Residue`, and
`Segment` properties. These methods predated the properties that replace
them, and this commit features deprecation warnings for each with
instructions on what to use instead.

Some `Atom` properties, such as `number`, `pos`, `serials`, have themselves been
replaced in the new scheme (`index`, `position`, `id`, respectively).

The methods `AtomGroup.translate` and `AtomGroup.rotateby` no longer
take tuples of `AtomGroup` objects as optional arguments, but only take
explicit vectors. Because `Residue`, `ResidueGroup`, `Segment`, and
`SegmentGroup` are no longer `AtomGroup`s themselves, leaving this in
creates a minor convenience at the cost of method complexity. The
documentation is correspondingly complex, and in the course of updating
the docstrings to numpy-style for #363, simplifying the method also
simplified the documenation.

Also deprecated `as_Universe` function. This has yet to be discussed on
the `issue-363` branch, but discussion should happen on what its purpose
is.

Not addressed in this commit:

1) In #363, `__getattr__` behavior for the Groups
have changed to a slightly different scheme. No warnings have been added
for this change to the `__getattr__` methods yet. The new scheme goes
as::

    SegmentGroups __getattr__ can select by segment name
    Segment __getattr__ can select by residue name
    ResidueGroup __getattr__ can select by residue name
    Residue __getattr__ can select by atom name
    AtomGroup __getattr__ can select by atom name

Should only require the following in `AtomGroup.__getattr__`, or
pehaps override in `ResidueGroup` and add after a `super`:

```python
if isinstance(self, ResidueGroup):
    warnings.warn("In version 0.15.0 this will select "
            "residue names, not atom names ", DeprecationWarning)
```


* Added deprecations to Residue angle methods.

The methods `phi_selection`, `psi_selection`, `omega_selection`, and
`chi1_selection` rely on particular atom names and the contiguity of
resids to work properly. Although these are not bad assumptions for most
topologies with a protein, they are inherently fragile. They have not
been included in the new topology system addressing #363.

* Added warnings for property access at the appropriate level.

Also added warning that getattr on ResidueGroups will work only for
residue names, not atom names.

* _FIFTEEN -> _SIXTEEN; Segment now has segid property

In the new topology scheme, atomid is just a label present defined by
the topology format (gro and PDB files have them) that don't need to
start from 0 or be unique. Atoms are uniquely identified by atom *index*
instead, which is mostly internal to the topology system but is unique
between atoms and starts from 0.

Given this, we make atom id in the old system roughly behave as it will
for the new scheme. Strangely, atom ids up until this point were defined
by residues. I have no idea why, or what a good reason might have been
for this.

* Added kwarg support to atom_property decorator

* Removed "id" from Atom slots.

Since `Atom.id` is now a property, it shouldn't be a slot.

* Added deprecations for Residue, Segment plural residue, segment props respectively

Since Residues are an AtomGroup subclass here, a Residue has e.g. `resids`,
which gives per-atom resids (all the same, *hopefully*). This doesn't
exist in #363, so added proper deprecations. Ditto for segment
properties that spit out per-residue results.

Also, since we don't want our own recommendations for setters using the
deprecated setters internally, did simple copy-paste of setter code to
appropriate property.

Also deprecated Residue.id, Residue.name, and added Residue.resid and
Residue.resname as the proper alternatives.

* Fixed neglected changes to copy-pasted code for property setters

* Removed deprecated use of Segment.id

* removed usage of deprecated functions Universe init

* Removed deprecations on anchor mechanisms.

The anchor mechanisms of a Universe deserve further discussion. They are
used for AtomGroup pickling/unpickling, which may or may not make sense
under the new system. De-deprecating for now, though.

* Added deprecations to changelog; fixed some omissions.

Also, moved warning decorator outside of cached decorator if present so
it displays every time.

Fix Merge for issue-363 branch (#781) * Fix Merge for issue-363 branch

Rewrote mda.Merge to work for new topology style.

I also changed the default argument for attrs in core.Topology() beacuse
the default argument of None caused an error, whereas using an empty
list instead will return a blank Topology.

* fix atomgrps for same universe, enable sum

My first attempt at collecting atom groups for the same universe was
flawed if args contained more than one atom group from the same
universe. Hopefully this one is correct.

I also override __rsum__ on AtomGroups to allow use of sum.

* cleanup and describe which topologyattr get Merged

* correct Merge atom order, segind, add top tests

I changed my previously proposed mda.Merge to align more closely with
the old Merge behavior, in that it preserves the atom order as given to
Merge. Given the introduction of residue and segment indices (distinct
from ids), the behavior of this new Merge assigns separate residue and
segment indices to each argument of Merge. That is, if two arguments to
merge are atomgroups from the same universe with the same residue
indices, in the post-merge universe, they will have different residue
indices. If the user doesn't want this, s/he should add together the
atom groups before merging.

My understanding is that resid is just an attribute of a residue,
whereas the residue index is the unique identifier of that residue
instance. I didn't think it would make much sense for Merge to duplicate
atoms by giving them different indices while keeping their residue
indices the same, such that you have doubled or tripled (etc.) the
number of atoms in a residue or segment.

Before I was sending the per-atom segment indices to Topology instead of
the per-residue segment indices. Topology.__init__() or
TransTable.__init__() should probably check that the correct length
index arrays are passed on.

I added an attribute to the TopologyAttrs called `per_object` where the
value of this attribute is 'atom', 'residue', or 'segment' if the length
of the TopologyAttr value should equal n_atoms, n_residues, or
n_segments. The Universe method `_process_attr` now checks if the
TopologyAttr has `per_object` attribute, and raises a ValueError of the
length of the value array is not as expected.

Finally I updated `test_modelling.py`. This actually increased the
number of errors raised during testing by 2, because instead of stopping
at an error in the first few lines of the test file, it goes on and
errors occur for Capping and `atoms.write`.

DATAWriter, velocity unit conversion, unit test Writes selection at current trajectory frame to file, including sections
Atoms, Masses, Velocities, Bonds, Angles, Dihedrals, and Impropers (if
these are defined). Atoms section is written in the "full" sub-style if
charges are available or "molecular" sub-style if they are not.
Molecule id in atoms section is set to to 0.

No other sections are written to the DATA file.
As of this writing, other sections are not parsed into the topology
by the `DATAReader`.

If the selection includes a partial fragment, then the outputted DATA
file will be invalid, because it will describe bonds between atoms
which do not exist in the Atoms section.

By default the writer assumes "conventional" or "real" LAMMPS units
where length is measured in Angstroms and velocity is measured in
Angstroms per femtosecond. If other units are desired, they must be
specified.

Raises ValueError if atom types are not convertable to integers or if
atoms of the same type don't all have the same mass.

An AttributeError will be raised if the atom group doesn't have masses.

I added tests to make sure topology attributes of the written file
(after being read again) match the topology attributes read from
the original file. Checks types, bonds, positions, velocities, etc.

There was a problem with test data mini.data because it had atom type
3 which had undefined mass, so I changed the atom type to 1.

The DATAParser before was not converting velocity units, so I added
default units Angstroms/fs which are the "real" units in LAMMPS.

replace unique_row with np.unique and np records The function `unique_row` was causing problems because bond type could
be None, and the containing numpy array had dtype==object. I replaced
`unique_rows` with `np.unique` by first converting the bond indices and
bond types into a numpy record, and then breaking this record back into
the bond indices and bond types.

I also simplified some of what I'd written in `topologyattrs.Bonds`.

Fix DATA type parsing and add explicit bond types **NOTE:** `atoms.bonds` is broken for atom groups without explicit bond typing
in this commit.

In order to write a LAMMPS.DATAWriter, I first need explicit typing of bonds,
angles, dihedrals, and impropers beyond the tupling of atoms types done now.
To hack bond types into the topology, I branched issue-363 and tried the
following:

1. Add optional `types` keyword to `topologyattrs.Bonds`. This is stored
in the class instance a `self._bondtypes`. A topology parser can pass `types`
to the Bonds topologyattr.
2. When `topologyattrs.Bonds` is called upon to generate a TopologyGroup,
these values are passed on via a new keyword in `TopologyGroup.__init__()`.
They are stored in the TopologyGroup instance as `self._bondtypes`.
3. I modified `TopologyGroup.__getitem__` to yield a Bond with attribute
`_bondtype`. If `_bondtype is not None` then it overrides the default behavior
of `bond.type`.
4. I modified `TopologyGroup()` calls wherever I could find them to pass on
`_bondtype` in the instantiation.

I found that the DATAParser in branch #363 is slightly broken, because
the atom types are saved as integers which breaks `select_atoms` (I think it
expects strings, and typing the types as strings on parsing fixes this issue).
It seems there is currently no test for atom selection from LAMMPS DATA files,
so this might have gone undetected.

An error is raised for `ag.bonds` for an atom group that doesn't have bonds,
but this seems to also be the case for branch issue-363 right now, so I didn't
try to fix this.

Two places are especially ugly. One is where I tried to hack `_bondtypes`
into the existing code to remove duplicate bonds. This is also where
the code seems to be broken for non-explicit bond types. In this case,
I set `_bondtypes` to be a numpy array full of `None` with `dtype=object`.
It seems that `unique_rows` fails for this case, although it works fine
when `_bondtypes.dtype == "|S1"`.

Make topology objects hashable on Python 3 On python 2, user defined object are hashable by default unless the
__hash__ method is overloaded to return None. On python 3, user objects
are not hashable if the __eq__ method is overloaded.

This commit defines a __hash__ method that returns a hash based on the
sorted indices of the atoms involved in the topology object. This should
reproduce the behavior advertised in the topology object documentation.
Yet, it is different from the previous behavior. In the previous behavior,
two different objects with the same atoms were equal for  __eq__ but
different regarding the hash.

Fix how unicode Angstrom symbol is encoded The unicode representation for the Angstrom symbol in the dictionary
used for unit conversion was wrong. While the escaping sequence was
correct, it was used as a series of bytes rather than like a unicode
string. Also, the same key was created twice as two escaping sequences
were used (utf-16 and utf-8) and they were synonymous.

The tests were passing because they were testing against the same series
of bytes.

This commit use a proper unicode string as key and remove the redundant
definition. It also adds a test with the actual unicode symbol rather
than an escaping sequence.

Make xrange and range call python 3 compatible The `xrange` function disapears in Python 3. In the same time, the
meaning of the `range` function changes in python 3 to behave in a
similar fashion as `xrange`. Therefore, in Python 3, `range` produces a
generator and `xrange` does not exist anymore.

This commit replace all calls to `xrange` by calls to `range`. It also
overload the `range` built-in  to use the one provided by `six` that
reproduce the behavior from Python 3.

No Cython file got touched, even though some use xrange, as xrange seems
to keep existing in Cython.

This commit changes the behavior of the `range` built-in!

In the future, `xrange` should not be used anymore. When `range` is
used, it should be overloaded with `from six.moves import range`. When a list
is needed rather than a generator, `list(range(x))` should be used.

Fix Cody/QC error with format Cody/QC suggested a fix to replace all string replacements using % by
string replacements using the `format` method. Yet, the suggested
replacement introduce a syntax error by replacing all occurences similar
to '%4s' to something like '{0:4!s}'; where what follows the column is
the format for the replacement and what follows the bang is the type for
the conversion.

Cody's replacement leads to the following exception:

    ValueError: Invalid conversion specification

It appears that the column part and the bang part of the format should
be written the other way around so '{0:4!s}' should actually be
'{0!s>4}'. Note that the > character is important as it describes how
the data should be aligned. By default, without the >, strings are flush
to the left while '%4s' flush strings to the right. Note that '{0!d:4}'
does flush to the right on the contrary to what happens with strings.

In MDAnalysis, the only faulty replacements where about string format.
They could be detected using the following grep statement:

    egrep -Ro '\{[^:}]*:[^!}]*![^}]*\}' *

I fixed the faulty replacement with the following command:

    find ./ -name '*.py' -exec \
        sed -rie 's/\{([^:}]*):([^!}]*)!s\}/{\1!s:>\2}/g' {} \;
Migrated `%` string formating

`ResidueGroup.masses` and `SegmentGroup.masses` work (automatic
aggregation of components), there's no need to define the same

adds only a single if statement to methods that already had list
comprehensions anyway, so shouldn't see a performance hit. This means we
don't have to do backflips for Residues and Segments to make downward
translations work, either.

MDAnalysis now truncates atom numbers when writing .gro files with more than 99,999 atoms, in a manner consistent with genbox in GROMACS 4.6.3. Note that it appears that some GROMACS utilities (i.e., trjconv) actually write 00000 instead of 0 for the 100,000th atom. Merge pull request #528 from cyanezstange/develop add ZeroDivisionError exception to WaterOrientationRelaxation class

Detailed rationale for the fix: @alejob thinks that the solution is a good option, because 
the problem is generated when in time t and in time t + dt there aren't repeated molecules
(and/or when there aren't molecules in the selection), so one can't evaluate time 
correlation. Usually in very small selections we have this problem that there aren't repeated
molecules in t and t + dt. With ignoring the division by zero we are just removing one point 
from the mean. This final mean is one point in our output graphic. So, for instance, instead 
of calculate the mean with 1000 points, we would calculate this mean with 994 points (6 zero division).

A user shouldn't select a so small group of atoms to run this analysis, but if he decides to make it, 
we have this solution.

Been hacking away at our new Universe, and trying to fix imports. Importing the module is broken at the moment, but we're getting there.
Most of what I've done here is to trim out anything that looked like it
needed major rethinking in Universe, especially the various caching it
was doing. My main goal was to cut as much as possible so we can focus
clearly on what Universe needs to do. In particular, I think Universe
should *not* store any kind of state on its own, but instead all its
state information is in its attached objects, specifically its Topology,
and trajectory Reader. We plan to rethink how bonds, angles, dihedrals

Hammering on Resids. Resids.set_atoms actually reassigns the atoms to different residues. At
the moment the residues must exist already in order for this to work; an
exception is raised if atoms are being assigned to non-existent
residues. This is also a slow operation, because we have to translate
the resids the atoms are being assigned to to the corresponding
resindexes, which are used to slice residue arrays. We are fine with
setting to be slow so long as getting (reading) is fast, however.
Merge branch 'issue-363' of github.com:MDAnalysis/mdanalysis into issue-363

Settled question on residue, segment non-membership. An atom must be a member of a residue, and a residue must be a member of
a segment. This has the consequence that there is at least 1 residue and
1 segment in the system. We conclude that this should work fine.

Perhaps there should always be at least one residue and segment in any
topology (index 0 in the residue and segment tables), with every atom

Building out generic TopologyAttr. We want to be able to construct Topology objects with attribute
handling, such as masses, charges, resids, etc., handled by individual
TopologyAttr objects. A topology parser will parse its file, build a
number of arrays to be fed to, say, Masses, Resids, Charges objects, and
then feed these to a Topology object. The Topology object can then be
given to a Universe as the core object for accessing and modifying the
topology. All the complexity of managing the arrays that contain
topology information is encapsulated inside the Topolgy object and its
TopologyAttrs.

-adapted netcdf float32 test for scipy.io.netcdf
 NOTE: currently fails for me on Linux (which might explain
       problems in #551) with the dtype('>f4') instead of
       np.float32 == dtype('<f4')
  so we need the next fix:
- more robust NCDFWriter dtype check: ignore byte-order
  The scipy.io.netcdf code appears to write out with dtype('>f4') (i.e.
  big-endian) whereas the native np.float32 is little-endian ('<f4').
  We now just test that both are 'float32' and ignore endianness by
  comparing dtype.name. This is a bit hackish but alternatively I would
  have to write a test that compares

    dtype.kind
    dtype.itemsize

  separately, and both appear to be captured in dtype.name succinctly.
  (see http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.10.0/reference/arrays.dtypes.html#attributes)

Default to occupancy=1 if not given in PDB This is the most permissive default I can think of. Imagine someone has
a pdb like this.

  ATOM      1 CA   LYS A  1    111    123   124   .5
  ATOM      1 CA   VAL A  1    111    123   124   .5
  ATOM      2 CA   ALA A  2    111    123   125
  ATOM      3 CA   CYS A  3    9      9     9     .9
  ATOM      3 CA   LYS A  3    9      9     9     .1

What should be the occupancy of the alanine? In the most probable cause
the author of the PDB thought it should be one. The occupancies are
afterwards added to the timestep object.

This also fixes another issue we might have had with the old code. It
was possible to have less occupancy values then atoms in a universe.
That should have triggered an error.

Fix circular import. The problem here is that an import statement actually EXECUTES all the
code that is defined inside of the modules __init__.py. The problem now
is that the lib module was loaded before the execptions were loaded,
note that lib/__init__.py now loads `NeighborSearch.py` which in return
loads `AtomGroup.py` which loads `SelectionError` which is defined later
int the top `__init__.py`. This means we have a circular import and
everything just stops working. By importing the exeptions first
everything will work fine.

Added corresponding changes for n_... to c sources. Also, tests appear to pass!

Switched to n_atoms, n_residues, n_segments, n_frames. To make access to the number of atoms, residues, or segments in an
atomgroup easier, we include convenience properties for getting at these
values. Now, instead of ``ag.numberOfAtoms()``, one need only call
``ag.n_atoms``. Likewise for number of residues and segments. Note that
these methods aren't completely necessary since AtomGroups,
ResidueGroups, and SegmentGroups have a ``__len__`` method, but
they are useful for introspection.

For consistency, we have also changed ``trajectory.numframes`` to
``trajectory.n_frames``.

Overhaul of the test subsystem. Implements nose plugins, as a submodule (closes #331).

Available plugins are: memleak testing, stderr capturing
 (for quieter test runs), and proper knownfailure implementation.

The test function is no longer imported from numpy. We
 roll our own that registers our external plugins.

Behavior was kept regarding parallel testing, labels, and invocation
 from the command line. stdout and stderr suppression was made default.

Running nosetests from the command line bypasses our test function,
 and plugins aren't loaded. Plugin-dependent code (the knownfailure
 decorator, for instance) is aware of this and behaves accordingly.

A command-line script mda_nosetests was added to the suite that acts
 as a replacement for the nosetests command, but is plugin-friendly.

Knownfailure usage was corrected (closes #338).

Added RMSF analysis class analysis.rms.RMSF (closes Issue #288) The RMSF class takes an atomgroup as input and then iterates through
that atomgroup's parent universe's trajectory (start, stop, step
supported). It obtains an RMSF for each atom in the atomgroup,
calculated across the iterated frames. The RMSF class features an
API similar to the RMSD class. At present it performs no fitting,
however, using only the atom coordinates as-is.

Added 'quiet' keyword to RMSF class. This is informally a standard
keyword for making these things suppress output.

XTC and TRR files now write offsets to disk. It is a common problem that if one has large XTC or TRR files, it can
take a long time to get the number of frames when loading these as
coordinates of a universe. Getting the number of frames is necessary for
the chain reader upfront, so when loading multiple XTC or TRR files this
may mean a substantial wait before the universe is ready for use.

When the number of frames is obtained, an index of the trajectory file
giving the offsets of its frames is also stored. This allows for quick
random access through the trajectory thereafter. Until now, this index
is lost when python session ends. Now, these offsets are stored as
(small) hidden pickle files in the same directory as the trajectories
with names ``.<nameoftrajectory>_offsets.pkl``.

When a universe is loaded with XTC or TRR files, the TrjReader tries to
load these offsets. If they are present, it then checks the ctime of the
trajectory file against that stored in the offset file. If they match,
the offsets are applied. Otherwise, they are ignored and eventually
overwritten when numframes is called.

Updated unit tests to reflect changes to offsets.

Added exception for storing xdrfile offsets.

This elegantly handles cases for which offsets cannot be automatically
stored in the same directory as the trajectory (due to permissions, for
example).

Added additional checks to ensure offsets are not stale.

In addition to ctime, the size of the trajectory file is also stored
with the offsets. On load the size and ctime of the trajectory file is
compared to these stored values.

Following load of the offsets, the last frame of the trajectory is
loaded. If this fails, then the offsets are dropped so they will be
regenerated. This is a final sanity check that the offsets aren't wrong.

Tests passing for xdrfile persistent offsets.

New tests added to ensure that offsets aren't used when stale.

Added "cached" decorator (Issue 207) cached decorator automates the use of cache within classes.

Usage:

[@property] - can work with cached too
@cached('_cache key')
def function(self, *args, **kwargs):
    # This code defines how to calculate the property
    # it will only be ran on the first call of it however
    # otherwise a cached value (stored under '_cache key') will
    # be returned.

Ie a class method call can become cached by adding a decorator with
single argument which is the key name it will be stored under.

Requires the class to have a cache dict called "_cache", no error
checking for this.

correct reading/writing of DCD unit cell information (fixes Issue 187) ATTENTION: Prior to this fix, triclinic box handling was BROKEN for DCDs. Orthorhombic boxes were ok because the order
           of the angles did not matter.

- in combination with the fixed DCD C code, the unit cell information is extracted from the DCD as
  [A,gamma,B,beta,alpha,C] and presented in the canonical format as [A,B,C,alpha,beta,gamma].
  (The changes in dcd.c were modelled after the 2013 version of the VMD molfile plugin.)
- the DCDReader heuristically guesses if new-style (at least CHARMM c36b) box matrix information is supplied
  and then converts on the fly to the  [A,B,C,alpha,beta,gamma] format
- the DCDWriter *always* writes writes  [A,gamma,B,beta,alpha,C] (in fact, the underlying C code in DCD.c, which is based
  on the VMD DCD molfile plugin) writes the angle cosines instead of the angles but it takes  [A,gamma,B,beta,alpha,C]
  as its input); the DCDWriter will not write box matrix to a DCD: this is not supported at the moment.

  NOTE: Therefore, if one reads a DCD and then writes it with MDAnalysis, it might not be identical because the unit cell
        information might have been converted from box matrix to lengths/angle cosines. This DCD file might then
        not be readable in CHARMM any more.

- added test cases for reading/writing triclinic boxes (files from the Issue 187 report;
  thanks to caioubiounb for providing a set of NAMD files)
- updated docs (lots of notes and links to Issue 187)

For further details and background see Issue 187.

Reworked Topology system - Topology information is now loaded lazily into the Universe.
  Can force universe to preload everything with u.load_topology()

- AtomGroups now have lazily built .bonds .angles .torsions & .impropers attributes

- TopologyDict (.bondDict etc) removed from AtomGroups in favor of new system.

- TopologyGroup now supports selecting all of a given bond type through
  the .selectBonds method

- Can select all bonds from a TopologyGroup which are in an AtomGroup with the
  .atomgroup_intersection() method.
  This also accepts the 'strict' keyword to force all members of all bonds within
  the returned TopologyGroup to feature in the queried AtomGroup.

Changes to some Parsers to homogenise ._psf outputs.

- Changed DMS and MOL2 parser to no longer create
  Bond instances into their parsing return, but instead
  create tuple of atom numbers in line with other parsers.

- Added _bondorder to u._psf.
  Parsers that want to add 'order' to bonds use this dictionary to do that
  All parsers now strictly pass a tuple of length 2 tuples to define bonds

Created TopologyObject.  Analogous to Atom object, smallest unit of Topology.

- Bonds Angles Torsions now subclass this.
- Added Improper_Torsions
- All TopologyObjects now use .atoms instead of .atom1 etc,
  This might break old code that looks for bond.atom1 for instance,
  use bond[0] in this case
- All TopologyObjects work nicely with __eq__ __contains__ etc
- Added lt and gt methods to TopologyObject.
  This now allows lists of them to be sorted(),
  TopologyGroup now sorts its input.
  This makes slicing work nicer, as order is more logical between
  different groups.

Improved guess_bonds, now scales O(n) wrt memory.
Added guess_angles, guess_torsions, guess_improper_torsions

Added lots of unit tests for topology, ~90% coverage.

DCDWriter workaround: new kwarg dt to set time between frames in ps NOTE: Currently, the DCDWriter breaks the docs of
      Writer() which state that "delta is given in ps"
      whereas the DCDWriter expects AKMA. Until we clean
      up the mess (see Issue 206), the dt keyword can
      be used as a workaround.

streams for coordinate topology readers and writers (streamIO) - new util.isstream() function with test case:
  Utility function to check if something is a filename or a proper stream. Useful for
  enhancements so that we can pass stream objects around instead of filenames.

- util.NamedStream with test case:
  wrapper class around a stream (eg cStringIO or file) that also provides a (fake)
  filename. Can be used to be dropped in the place of filename if the underlying
  code uses openany(). Will not work with C-code that does its own fopen().

- new MDAnalysis.StreamWarning (used in NamedStream)

- util.filename(): can deal with NamedStream

- util.anyopen(): changed return values (INCOMPATIBLE TO PREVIOUS)

  To streamline the use of anyopen() the function now returns only
  the stream instead of a tuple (stream, filename) as before.

  This will BREAK OLD CODE although the impact is probably small
  as the function was not used widely and within in MDAnalysis was
  only called wrapped in openany() (pre 0.8.2).

- using util.openany() or util.anyopen() instead of open()/file() in
  any Python-based coordinate and topology IO (excludes DCD, XTC/TRR,
  netcdf): can use compressed files automagically

- with stream-enabled open functions it is possible to use streams in
  many places by simply providing util.NamedStream (which can wrap
  a cStringIO buffer or a urllib2.urlopen instance)

  EXPERIMENTAL feature; wrap a stream into util.NamedStream and
  construct a Universe from the stream.

New feature: capping proteins An example script is added showing how MDAnalysis can be used to modify a
simple peptide and add terminal caps to it. The peptide is AAQAA3 and the
caps are ACE and NMA.

- check number of atoms after capping (compare to maestro output),
- check if box dimensions were changed.

New feature: MOL2 format support MOL2 molecular structure format, developed by Trips,
is used to store structures of small molecules and proteins.

Mol2 files can have multiple blocks, with different number of atoms,
much like MAE files. This is not supported. Similarly to PDB reader,
only multi-molecule mol2 files with the same number of atoms are supported.

- Basic unit testing, tests for corrupt mol2 files. Added support for atom selections,
- Added example to the Mol2 reader docs,
- Mol2Parser is a class,
- Parser errors are just exceptions.

Added copy_slice(slice) method to base.Timestep (Fixes Issue 163) This method creates a new Timestep which has all header information and a portion (defined by slice)

information that was possible to include. (Fixes Issue 163)

AtomGroup.bond(): renamed keyword minimage to pbc for consistency All other methods that take periodicity into account are taking the pbc=True keyword.
Bond used minimage=True for the same purpose. Even though the underlying approach is
different (using packIntoBox() vs code directly available to distance_array()) from
a users point of view the behavior is the same and therefore should use the same
keywords. (Also, bond(minimage) was only introduced in 0.8 so this is unlikely to break
any existing code.

when calculating minimum image convention.

AtomGroup.packintobox() renamed to packIntoBox for consistency

packIntoBox() now has inplace flag which works similarly to
coordinates.core.convert_to_native().  True changes the coordinates
whereas False just returns them

AtomGroup.bond() now has minimage flag.  If true will account for minimum
image when calculating bond distance.

Lots of AtomGroup methods now have a pbc flag.  If true, this will move
atoms within the primary unit cell before the rest of the calculation.
This is false by default, so default behaviour has not changed.

changed how we handle knownfailure tests due to missing executable - HOLE test: test_analysis.TestHoleModule.test_hole_module_fd_closure(): replaced
  the knownfailure() decorator from a27e92637544a86af0a181e4544f418a438a356
  with the numpy decorator

     @dec.skipif(executable_not_found_runtime("hole"))

  because the @knownfailure(msg, OSError) decorator even skipped the test if the
  HOLE binary was available. This makes use of the new executable_not_found_runtime()
  helper factory function.

  Also skip this test if we cannot set the rlimits with another skipif() that
  looks at the helper function rlimits_missing().

- protected test_analysis.TestAlignmentProcessing.test_fastta2select_ClustalW()
  with a check that the ClustalW binary can be found.

- added a factory function executable_not_found_runtime() that can be used with the
  numpy test decorator skipif():

    @dec.skipif(executable_not_found_runtime("binary_name"), msg="skip test because binary_name not available")
    def test_something(self, ...)

  It uses the new helper executable_not_found().

  If someone has a better grip on decorators than I then they might be able to roll skipif()
  and (executable_not_found_runtime() together in another decorator such as "skipifnoexe()".

Below are notes on the various parts of the conversion process
in which as simple script was inflated into a whole package
(with the idea that this would make it easier to add new rotamer

- heavily modified the covolve-mtss script

  - moved script code into a if __name__ == "__main__" block
  - added copyright and authorship
  - changed the calling signature of script: provide topology and
    trajectory or multiple trajectories as arguments; removed the
    --pdbfile argument (needs MDAnalysis 0.8 for concatenating
    multiple trj files on the fly)
  - use quiet option to suppress output from rms_fit_trj()
    (needs MDAnalysis 0.8)
  - new option to specify the rotamer library directory
  - use logging
  - updated example with new option and README insted of the
    shell script

- for the future: combined rotamer lib into TRR
  - Coordinates are kept in framse and the occupancy of each rotamer in the lambda (Timestep.lmbda)
  - not used yet but see code in the data directory

- Split into a package and a small script, convolve-mtss-rotamers.py

  - created the rotamers package with rotamers.library and rotamer.convolve
  - rotamers.library is responsible for loading rotamer libraries; at the
    moment, only 'MTSSL 298K' is available but more can be added
  - library files live in the data/ directory and are installed with
    the package. New library metadat must be added to rotamers.library.LIBRARIES
  - rotamers.convolve contains most of the original code but packaged as
    a class RotamerDistance
  - added copyright blurb and info messages
  - tested (see doc/example/README) and get same result as before

- setuptools installable package

- plot distribution

- added MDAnalysis>0.7.7 to requirements

  NOTE: uses features that are currently in the 0.8-dev development version

- added installation instructions

- reorganized example and wrote primitive shell test script

- changed library: Only prepend [0] to weights and not [0,0]

  - The first frame of the rotamer library trajectory is (apparently)
    just a (ideal?) structure; rotamers start at the second frame.

detect OpenMP-capable compiler during setup (fixes Issue 145) The cython-produced c code guards all of its openmp pragmas and
function calls with #ifdef _OPENMP
e.g https://code.google.com/p/mdanalysis/source/browse/package/src/numtools/distances_parallel.c#2603),
which is set only when -fopenmp is passed as a flag to the compiler.
So it's fine to compile the "parallel cython" code on compilers that
don't support openmp -- if its not available or you don't pass -fopenmp,
you will just get a serial version.

The key is to dynamically detect the compiler capabilities.
The attached patch file detects whether the compiler supports openmp,
and inserts the -fopenmp. Some compilers also require linking against
libgomp, so it's good to check for that too.

fixed memory blowup in the unit tests (introduced in commit 1e05654b23e2) Running the unit tests (specifically, test_coordinates.py) would consume ~8 GB
of memory because the memory for the created universes was not freed (despite
the tearDown methods: apparently something kept a reference to the universe alive
and garbage collecting could not kick in). The culprit turned out to be a a
__del__() method that I had added to Universe "just to make sure that trajectories
are closed". Somehow this method kept a universe alive in a TestCase. The
Universe.__del__ method was removed and the test cases all run fine (and consume
about 800 MB in total).

applications library The applications/ directory contains self-contained Python packages
that make use of MDAnalysis as their primary dependency. Each package
should be installable on its own but make use of dependency mechanisms
to automatically install MDAnalysis (and other required packages).

The idea is that an interested use can easily install a particular
application without having to worry too much about MDAnalysis itself.

See the toplevel README.txt for more details.

fixes Issue 122 by making netCDF4 an optional dependency netcdf4 python requires both HDF5 and netcdf, which can be difficult
to compile. MDAnalysis only needs netcdf for the AMBER ncdf Reader/Writer
so we make this dependency optional and later raise a error if the user
tries to read/write a ncdf trajectory. This approach makes MDAnalysis
compile out of the box on most machines but imposes a post-installation
burden on AMBER users.

- netCDF4 can be automatically installed with

    cd MDAnalysis-0.7.7
    easy_install --user . MDAnalysis[AMBER]

  (i.e. netCDF4 has become a extra_requires package, tagged with 'AMBER')

fixes Issue 107: read NAMD/VMD space separated PSF files NAMD/VMD uses their own "PSF" file format, which is space separated and not
fixed column (as the original CHARMM/XPLOR specification). Such files
would lead to a ValueError in the PSF reader. They are produced when very
long atom type names (from CGENFF in conjunction with the XPLOR alphanumeric
atom types) are used.

The PSF parser was changed to explicitly use a detected format (CHARMM standard
or EXT) or NAMD. From VMD 1.9.1 the VMD psfpluging adds the flag "NAMD" to the
PSF header so we can detect the format as usual. Older files are precariously
detected: We assume standard format (or EXT if the EXT flag was found). The
first ValueError triggers a switch to the NAMD format for the rest of the file.
A warning is issued (and logged if logging is enabled).

Logging was added to the PSFParser and a new warning, FileFormatWarning created.

The test case for the namd_cgenff example files now passes.

Writers do not modify coordinates in place anymore Writers for formats where the native units are different from MDAnalysis used
to convert the coordinates and time in place (faster and saves memory). However,
this will lead to problems if the timestep is analysed AFTER it was written
to disk. Even though no Issue has been filed, this was corrected as it is
very unintuitive behavior and could lead to very weird bugs. If performance
is a issue please file a bug report.

The convert_to/from_native() methods were changed to
1) accept a inplace=True|False keyword; the default (as before) is
   True so that operations are in place
2) if no conversion takes place then we do not even perform the
   multiplication by 1 and just return the reference to the input
   (even if inplace=False)

Experimental PrimitivePDBReader/Writer: Support for r/w of multiframe PDB files Summary
PDB files with multiple MODEL entries can be read in: coordinates for the first frame are stored, for the reminder the starting line is stored, which allows the PDB file to be read when a particular frame is called for. No checking is done if the PDB changes in between frame reads (file is not locked), only integrity check is the atom number (shouldn't change between the frames). This is in disagreement with the API which uses file locks extensively. Writing of a selection of atoms and/or frames is also supported.

upgraded some analysis depedencies to be installed right away A number of packages that are used in the MDAnalysis.analysis module have been moved
into the setuptools requirement section so that they are immediately installed when
MDAnalysis is installed so that users can immediately access most of the functionality.
All these packages are available from PyPi and are typically Python-only or are known
to install via setuptools without problems in general.
More complicated packages (more elaborate compilation, use of optimised libraries) are
left in the optional section because it is assumed that the user will install them
through a package management system or manually. These packages are at the moment
  * matplotlib
  * scipy

fix for Issue 48 (sparse contact_matrix in distances.py) The sparse_contact matrix method, from distances.py, has been changed from
pure python. For large systems (CG bilayers with ~30k lipid atoms) the
calculation of the contact matrix with pure python code took too long.

Solution was written using python.scipy.weave module, which allows
compilation and execution of c code (stored as a string inside python
script).

Added a test case, after manually inspecting the data.

removed core.rms_fitting The old rms_fitting module has been superceded by the qcprot module.
Feedback from the mailinglist indicated that this module is not used
anymore
http://groups.google.com/group/mdnalysis-discussion/browse_thread/thread/b120747ffccfc340
Because this is the only module that requires LAPACK (which can be a pain
to install) we are removing the whole module ahead of schedule (originally
the removal was planned for release 0.8) to immediately improve installation.

Examples were updated accordingly: rmsd.py shows how to just calculate the
RMSD over a trajectory, rmsfit.py the trajectory fitting; rmsfit_alignment.py
was removed because all functionality is MDAnalysis.analysis.align.

fixed Issue 59 (naveen.michaudagrawal) -- DCDWriter now checks input coordinate array for continguousness - Because DCD's store the data in fortran format, ie a single timestep is (x,x,x,..., y,y,y..., z,z,z...) and through the magic of numpy arrays that's usually transparently handled.   The DCD writer is a bit brain dead when it comes to writing a trajectory. When I wrote the c interface to dcd writer I just took the ts._x, ts._y, ts._z arrays and assumed they were contiguous. However, the xtc data comes as (x,y,z, x,y,z, ...) and so the individual coordinate arrays are discontiguous in memory. So the easy solution is to check the flags argument of the _x, _y, _z arrays in DCDWriter and make a copy if they aren't contiguous.

- added new unit test (passes with Naveen's patch)

use PrimitivePDBReader as default PDB reader - Bio.PDB's reader can drop atoms when they have the same name   in a residue (which happens for systems generated from MD simulations)   The PrimitivePDBReader copes just fine with thos cases (but does   not handle esoteric PDB features such as alternative atoms and   insertion codes that are not needed for handling MD simulation data). - The default behaviour of MDAnalysis can be set through the flag       MDAnalysis.core.flag['permissive_pdb_reader']   The default is True. - One can always manually select the PDB reader by providing the   permissive keyword to Universe; e.g. Universe(...,permissive=False)   will read the input file with the Bio.PDB reader. This might be   useful when processing true Protein Databank PDB files. git-svn-id: https://mdanalysis.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@530 dcee7792-c13e-0410-88f5-272e5f544b36

writing of selections to trajectories - Writer class gained new high-level write() method which can take   either a Timestep, a Universe, or a AtomGroup. The atoms contained in   the argument are written as the next frame to the trajectory. - AtomGroup gained the "ts" property, which builds a Timestep on the fly   only containing the coordinates of the atoms in the group. frame and   unitcell are copied from the parent trajectory. - At the top level, import the coordinates.core.writer() factory function   as Writer to make it clearer for the user that it provides a Writer()   class instance. - updated Trajectory API (and all writer classes) git-svn-id: https://mdanalysis.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@465 dcee7792-c13e-0410-88f5-272e5f544b36
